---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base title="About" description="Resolute Ambitions exists to advance education and relieve financial hardship for future U.S. military officers.">
  <section class="page-intro">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="eyebrow dark">About</div>
      <h1>A calling shouldn't come with a credit balance.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Commitment to military service is a call to serve — not the most financially attractive career path for many. Resolute Ambitions exists to change the decision calculus for elite candidates and to help those who do choose service enter the fleet focused on being the best warfighting leader they can be.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Our purpose</h2>
      <p>
        The Resolute Ambitions Project exists to advance education and relieve financial hardship by providing scholarships to:
      </p>
      <ul class="checked">
        <li>High school students who demonstrate intent to pursue military officer commissioning through ROTC or service academy preparation programs.</li>
        <li>Active-duty enlisted service members seeking to complete or pursue collegiate education required for officer commissioning through programs such as Green to Gold, Seaman to Admiral (STA-21), OCS, and OTS.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why this work matters</h2>
      <p>
        Research indicates roughly 70–75% of military officers enter service carrying student loan debt. While service academies and full ROTC scholarships provide comprehensive educational funding, those opportunities are limited — academies produce only ~15% of new officers each year, and only ~25–27% of ROTC scholarship applicants receive an award.
      </p>
      <p>
        Officers commissioning through OCS or OTS must complete a bachelor's degree at their own expense before entry. Average student debt for officers from non-scholarship paths ranges from $25,000 to $40,000 — substantially higher for those at elite institutions or in specialized fields like law and medicine.
      </p>
      <div class="callout">
        Our military leaders disproportionately come from middle- and lower-income backgrounds. The cost of the collegiate requirement, modest early-career pay, and the practical impossibility of meaningful side income during active service combine into a real decision barrier — one that can deter candidates who would otherwise answer the call.
      </div>
      <p>
        Many honor their calling by accepting they must carry substantial debt while managing the early start-up costs of a military career: uniforms, family moves, continuing education. Resolute Ambitions is about changing that math.
      </p>

      <h2>How we operate</h2>
      <p>
        The organization is governed by a volunteer Board of Directors and operates with minimal administrative overhead to maximize scholarship funding. Initial operations are conducted by volunteers; paid staff will be hired only as growth warrants and funds permit. Scholarship funds are disbursed directly to accredited institutions on behalf of recipients — never to individuals — and enrollment and academic progress are verified before each disbursement.
      </p>

      <h2>Status</h2>
      <p>
        Resolute Ambitions has filed for 501(c)(3) recognition. Incorporation and EIN are in progress. Contributions made now will be retroactively tax-deductible to our filing date upon IRS approval. Please consult your tax advisor.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
